segments.text: And we're sitting in the living room of the Rogers residence getting ready for me to interview John Rogers about his experiences here first as a student and then as a member of the professional staff and faculty.
Now, John, would you say a sentence?
We'll test your recorder.
I came to A&M in 1936.
Okay, now.
I attended Rice from 1933 to 1936 and then transferred to A&M in the fall of 36.
I came to A&M in 1936 and went to school for two years to complete my bachelor's degree in 1938.
Okay.
Do I need to talk louder?
No, just hold it up.
John, to begin with, would you give a stranger who might listen to this or read it later a summary of where you grew up and get us to A&M?
Your growing up and your Rice experience and what you majored in and then
We'll move you up here.
All right, Haskell, I'll be glad to do that.
Just briefly, I was born in Arkansas.
I want to be sure and get that on the record.
My father was a Presbyterian minister, so we moved around quite a bit and lived in Oklahoma when I was real young and started to school and then moved to Houston, Texas when I was
in about the third grade, I believe that was back in 1925.
I went through regular school, on through high school, graduating from John Reagan High School in 1933.
And I went on to school then at Rice, since as you know Rice University is located in Houston and is quite a good school, and certainly a motivating force in 1933.
was the fact that nobody had any money.
So I could go to Rice for not much more expense than I actually had in high school.

At the time, Rice had no tuition, and you may recall that the founder, William Morris Rice, had established the institution as a means of helping students who were unable to afford college education otherwise.
So one stipulation was that
no tuition was to be charged.
I attended Rice just taking an academic course, I believe that's what it was called in those days, for three years.
You can well wonder how being raised in Houston, that was a big city even then comparatively, would be interested in agriculture, but I spent a lot of summers on the
grandparents farm in Arkansas and always been associated with farms and agricultural life.
Also, moving around a lot, I didn't have any one
place as a base, at least to some extent, so I always felt Arkansas was sort of home, since my parents were both from there and all their forebears.
Anyway, after spending the summer of, I believe it was 1936, on the farm in Arkansas, I decided, well, I'd go into agriculture.

I was ready to start farming, as far as that goes, but my father was a factor at that time, and while he never did absolutely insist on something, he strongly encouraged it, plus the fact that he was paying the bills.
So we came up to A&M
evaluate the situation in the summer of 36, and sure enough, I started A&M then in the fall of 1936 as a transfer student from Rice.
Describe that visit up here.
What did you do?
How did you get here?
What did you do?
Who showed you around?
Well, again, let me remind you, this was 1936, so that's 60-something years ago.
Anyway, my father and I drove up here,
And I don't believe either one of us had ever been to the A&M campus prior to that.

And I recall looking around the campus and going to the administration building, which was the main building at that time, and where all the administrative offices and the registrar's office was located.
And somehow we got an audience with the current registrar, E.J.
Howell, whom I'm sure...
you're familiar with and is well known in Aggieland and so forth.
So we visited with him for, I don't know, a couple hours, I'd say.
He was very considerate and I was surprised that a registrar at that time would be willing to spend a couple hours with some individual student just wanting to transfer to A&M.
But I'd say he did a real good job of it.
Everything seemed to work out well, so we decided on the way home that that's where I'd go.
So that was probably up in August, late August then, so I came on up here in a couple of weeks.
Did you walk around the campus, you and your dad?
I don't recall walking, no, I don't believe so.
We may have driven through it.
Of course, there wasn't nearly as much on the campus, so to speak, as there is today, but
I really don't have much recollection other than the conversation with the registrar.
That made quite an impression on us, and we remembered that.
So then you come back soon after that first visit to enroll.
Describe that arrival and how you got located into a dormitory and so forth.
Well, I guess the first statement I'd like to make, being a transfer student at A&M is a challenge.
Well, let me talk about the enrollment first, since it involves one of the historical A&M faculty.
I went through the registration line along with the other students and signed up for courses, various ones that the advisors counseled me I could take.
And of course, fitting a schedule in is a real challenge, especially
I'd already been to college three years, so I didn't want to spend the rest of my life taking undergraduate courses.
So I wanted to get as much credit, one, as I could from the Rice courses, and also to enroll for as many courses per semester.
So I had a schedule all figured out that finally totaled 23 hours.
I believe that's correct.
I really do.
And it was a real challenge.
to fit that many in that would apply on my degree.

And I finally got this all done and went around to get the final approval from some of the authorities, and I happened to encounter Dean Bolton, whom everyone knew at the time, and of course since then, he later became president.
Well, he's a fine old man, but I surely got aggravated with him that day.
He looked at my...
My schedule and transcript and so forth said well i'm sorry you're a transfer student here so we're not sure that you can meet the challenges of the nm academic.
situation so we're going to have to reduce your hours.
And I immediately bristled up at this.
Gee, I made good grades at Rice.
What are you talking about?
It didn't seem to have much impact on him.
Maybe negative.
I'm not sure.
But I remember the incident real well at the time.
But he won out.
He was in charge and I wasn't.
And I think he cut the hours back to 18 and said, well, we'll see how you do this semester.
Then we'll
Let it go on from there, and I might add, I took 23 hours every other semester as an undergraduate at A&M.
Now, your major at Rice was listed as what?
Academic, just what you'd call liberal arts.
I just took conventional courses, English, foreign language, a science course.
Then up here, what was your major?
Agronomy.
Describe...
for someone that might not have known Dean Bolton, describe him physically and his characteristics?
Well, I'm sure you're familiar with his name, the student name given to him, Bear Tracks, and he was like that somewhat.
He was a very bulky sort of fella, not real tall.
I don't
He was under six feet, I would think, but very broad and muscular, strout-looking individual and somewhat gruff in his speech, but I came to know him much better after the years following.
In fact, we went to the same church for a while, and he's just a wonderful person.
He was a stickler for rules, and whatever the book said, that was going to be it.
Where did you live that first year?
I lived in Law Hall.
Is it still standing?
I believe so.
It seemed like they were going to tear some of those halls down.
I'm not sure whether it is or not.
Whether it survived or not, there was quite an opposition to tearing some of them down.
What outfit was that?
2nd Headquarters Field Artillery.
Do you have any idea how you got assigned to that unit?
Yes.
Before I came up to school here,

say a couple weeks before I'd already decided to go here and I knew a number of friends from the John Reagan era lived in Houston Heights there who were in A&M so I counseled some of them and talked to them and there were a number of the local boys in that particular battery, the headquarters battery so I guess I just requested it and was able to get in.
I think they would let you go where you wanted to as long as there was
no reason to exclude you or if there was room in that particular outfit for you.
Describe the life of a transfer in 1936.
Confusing.
And sometimes difficult.
I'll do the best I can on that.
The system at that, particularly at that time where it was all core and all masculine, there might have been a, I could probably count the
quote, day students on my hand.
There were students who lived in the project houses, but they were in the ROTC also.
So it was for all practical purposes, 100% core members.
A transfer doesn't have a home.
You don't fit in anywhere.
You're not a fish.
And, you know, there's a certain camaraderie among the fish.
They all suffer, and they all serve, and they commiserate with each other.
Well, they didn't know exactly at the time where to put me.
I'd say when I moved in the first day of school, I was placed in a room with two fish, and I was a fish at that time, I guess you'd say, and stayed there for years.
I'd say a couple of months, quite a little while.
And I don't know just how or why this came about.
I guess the battery officers and some of the faculty decided that juniors, I was a classified junior at that time,
should be a fish and living with fish, and I guess relegated would be a reasonable term to all the activities that the fish encountered at that time.

So after about two months, they decided, well, I shouldn't be treated as a fish, but I wasn't quite an upperclassman either because I'd never gone through the fish ordeal, which is fair enough, I'd say.
So I was put in a room with two juniors who probably weren't too thrilled about this since they were bona fide A&M juniors, whereas I was a transfer junior.
They may have called me a junior fish at that time.
I'm not sure just what I recall.
I've heard that a transfer is sometimes called a frog.
Were you called a frog?
Never to my recollection, and my...
definition of a frog was one who started at midterm at that time.
That's the only particular term.
Did you get any hazing, initiation like a freshman would?
Yes.
When I was living as a freshman, I adhered to all the freshman requirements.
I had a room to clean up along with my roommates and of course we're
and had to meet all the, say, freshman requirements.
You couldn't go to bed before, I don't remember, 10 o'clock, 10.30, and had to be in bed by 11, and had to be up at 6 and get the rooms cleaned up, and all the other various things that freshmen did.
Oh, I remember one incident where I certainly qualified as a freshman.
Are you familiar with the...
concept of airing out.
At that time, I don't know how long it was carried on, but the fish were required to leave the dormitory about, I think, four or five in the morning.
This was later in the year.
I think it was in the spring, but it was still kind of chilly, and all of us were
Run out of the dormitory with practically no clothes on.
I think I had a pair of shorts, literally, was all I had.
And we were driven down to, my recollection is Wellburn or Milliken, somewhere down the road there, and just dumped out unceremoniously on the highway.
And that was kind of an experience to get your attention.
But I was fortunate.
I got out on the highway and thumbed a ride, and some trucker stopped.
I guess he was considerate anyway.
He wondered what anybody was doing out there without any clothes on that time of day and brought me back to A&M.
When there was a paddle session...
Did you get treated those first weeks like a freshman when the paddles were brought out?
I was paddled a few times, but not to the extent the regular fish were.
At that time, I was paddling all up and down the river.
All the classes, seniors paddled juniors, juniors paddled sophomores, et cetera.
So I think I got my share as a junior fish, so to speak, when I got up there.
But I didn't get nearly the amount that the regular fish did.
Do you have a recollection of what the cost was of that first year for you and your family?
I think it's about $50 a month for everything, but I have the figure $400, $450 for a year.
Did you have any spending money, a kind of an allocation?
No.
I don't recall a whole lot.
My parents were supporting me in school.

I had worked, of course, before when I lived in Houston and had some money, but there wasn't a whole lot you could spend money on there unless you left town on the weekends, which I didn't do so much my first semester.
I guess it's true of most Aggies.
After you stay a while, you leave more and more frequently on the weekends.
Academically, how did you find the rigor of the A&M academic program compared to the Rice program?
Rice is a more rigorous academic school, and I don't mean that as a derogatory remark about the A&M.
The courses varied quite a bit, and there'd be some courses that would be comparable to the Rice courses.
If you'll permit me to tell you one story about, this relates to Rice, but it bears on.
At Rice, I was taking academic courses, and you're required to take one science course each year.
This doesn't speak too highly of me, but anyway, I got to my junior year, and I was looking for a science course that didn't have a lab.
I wasn't to an average spending a full afternoon in a lab, so...
I ended up signing up for a psychology course, since it's construed as a science.
That may be debatable, but anyway.
It was a big class, two or three hundred people in the lecture, and I believe the professor's name was Dr. Patty.
just to show that Rice is not all top notch.
He was not a good prof in all fairness.
And I was not a good student either, I might add in that case.
Anyway, this is my junior year, and at Rice they grade by one, two, three, or did them by one, two, three, four, five.
And I had done reasonably well my first two years, but the junior year I was,

doing better i guess i'd gotten accustomed to the situation some i was taking five courses at the time and they don't give you any grades still well they give you grades the end of the semester but the courses were all year courses you stayed them all year so my i got my report card at the mid mid year and it had four ones and a five in psychology
I knew I hadn't done well.
It was a lost cause as far as I was concerned, but I did want to pass the course.
There was a rule at Rice then as a junior, you could only take five courses.
If you failed one of your five courses, you had to drop one and only go back to four, the theory being that you weren't
capable of keeping up with five, so you go back to four.
So I went into the registrar and he looked at that report card and just shook his head and said, what's the matter with you?
If you can make ones in other four courses, surely you can do better than a failing grade in psychology.
I said, well, I really haven't done well.
And I just wanted to be sure I didn't have to drop the course though.
So he said, well, you go around to your psychology prof and

talk to him about it see what he says so i went around to the prof now i'll never forget his expression that day he looked at the report card and then saw the five on there for psychology and then finally looked at happened to see my name rogers oh rogers i remember now i said you know what you did you took my core of my psychology course for a whole semester and when you wrote the

name of the course on your term on your term exam you spelled it piscology and said i'm not going to pass anybody you can't even spell spell the name of the course after taking it a full full semester i got the biggest kick out of that but that was a that was a fact that no but see i had another semester you let me stay in there and i i finally ended up with a four but i
I learned how to spell psychology out of it.
Now, you were a junior.
You took two undergraduate years here.
Correct.
But I took almost the equivalent of, I don't know, at least two and a half by taking excessive hours per semester.
During those two years,
who were some of the key faculty and staff members that you now remember proudly?
Who were some of the good people that you encountered?
During my two years of undergraduate work,

uh... let me start in some sequence or i'll forget some and i think i can remember them pretty well while i was majoring in agronomy so uh... dr trotter was the head of the agronomy teaching department at that time and i've always held him in high regard i didn't take any courses under him but i had p trotter and uh... others in the agronomy department
took courses under and were excellent professors.
Dr. Luther Jones, I'm sure you've run into him in some of your discussions with other people.
He was a soil professor there, although he's better known for lending money to students and faculty and anyone else who will borrow from him to obtain houses and go through school and so forth.
Cotton Joe Mogford, if you're
recall that name, was also in the department at that time, and he was the cotton expert, very fine gentleman.
R.C.
Potts, who later became dean of agriculture, I'm sure you know him, was one of the professors there, and he had just started.
He was fairly young and come down from Oklahoma in him at the time.
Did he have a nickname?
I don't recall it if he did.
I don't remember hearing about him.
R.C.
No, I believe that he was a grass expert, but I don't remember anyone giving him that nickname.
Red Thompson was another.
I don't know whether you've heard of him much or not.
He later went on to Iowa State at Ames and became, I guess he was dean of agriculture up there in the administration.
Those were the main professors in the agronomy department itself.
I don't remember the names of a lot of the professors in some of the other areas.
I do remember the
chemistry professors, if you need to hear anything about them.
Well, Dr. Hedges was head of the Department of Chemistry, and the student name for him was Steppenhalf, which I'm sure you've run into before.
Kind of a thoughtless name for him since he was crippled and shuffled along like that.
R.C., I've forgotten his initials, Snuggs, I don't know whether you've run into him, encountered him as another of the chemistry profs.
And perhaps the most colorful was Heddy and Jones.
No?
Well, gee, I thought everybody knew him.
That was his student name, Head End Jones.
I believe he was the one that lived on the campus and had all the roses there.
No, maybe not.
Anyway, he was an unusual character.
quite volatile in the way he described things or discussed them.
He mainly taught laboratory.
I remember one incident where we were running some kind of experiment in the lab and
You know, chemistry is a little uncertain a lot of the time, so all of us were asking him what to do and this, that, and the other in the laboratory.
And some student, fortunately it wasn't me this time, asked him about what shall I do about this acid.
He had a beaker full of it or something.
He hit in and said, well, don't you know?
I said, I'm sorry, I just don't know what to do.
He said, well, go ahead, pour it in the pot.
The container over there, smoke filled the room and everything.
Now you'll know how to find out things.
That would be typical of him.
He'd be glad to tell you to do something to emphasize it.
Anyway, I almost lived in the chemistry lab or department one semester.
It seemed like I was making up hours in chemistry that I hadn't had previously.
I had at least three courses over there, I know of.
As you look back on your life, which of those undergraduate courses was the most important to you?
I haven't come to that one yet, and I'll go ahead and mention it.
My genetics course was, and the one professor to which I attribute having the most impact and actual effect on my life
was Professor C.B.
Godbey.
I don't know whether you, well, he's a wonderful person and a marvelous teacher.
And as an aside, I never have taken this on as a project, but like he's someone the university should really recognize for what he did during his career here.
He was very mild-mannered, unassuming person.

and didn't project himself but any of the agricultural students and particularly on into graduate school will just held him in the highest regard both personally and professionally anyway i happen to have him as my genetics professor and i enjoyed genetics
and did reasonably well in it.
And it was Mr. Godby who recommended me for an assistantship and to go on to graduate school and therefore enabled me to start a career after college.
So I really am most in debt to him as one individual.
And I'd say the people in the agronomy department, Potts, Trotter, Jones, and so forth,
Was there anyone outside the faculty that you learned to turn to for advice?
Was there anyone anywhere else?
On the campus, for example?
Well, yes, I would say M.L.
Cashin was one that I talked to.
Describe Mr. Cashin.
Well,
He was just a wonderful individual and I'll tell you how I came in contact with him initially and then I continued to visit with him during my years here.
My father knew him or knew of him and they traced back to North Carolina relations and I guess they thought they might have even had some common relations anyway when
My father was here on the campus a time too, very early when I was in school.
He looked up Mr. Cashin and introduced me to him.
So I always felt like I could go to him and did.

talked to him at times and he was just just a great person thought so much of students and being in the center of the campus there at YMCA well I know he was a tremendously positive force for all A&M students.
Physically if I I never did know him
Would the two sons that you and I do know, are they similar in appearance to their father?
I don't remember Mr. Cashin having red hair, but in fact, he didn't have much hair at all, as I recall him.
Jim reminds me more of his father than Red does.
I don't know.
It would be interesting to see what they think, but...
And it seems to me it has more of the characteristics of his father, just a real solid, wonderful individual, and always wanted to be helpful and to think of the other people.
I believe Red probably is more forceful or outgoing, and I guess their careers probably illustrate this.
And who was, during those student days, who was the president?
